  "prompt": "Will ISPs block Facebook when we lose net neutrality?",
  "response": "If net neutrality regulations were to be fully repealed, ISPs (Internet Service Providers) could have the ability to block or prioritize certain websites and online services. However, whether they would specifically block Facebook or any other platform would depend on a range of factors, such as business agreements, competitive dynamics, and user demand.\n\nWithout net neutrality, ISPs might charge extra fees for access to certain popular services, create bundled service packages, slow down competitors' services, or favor their own content. Blocking well-known, widely-used services like Facebook entirely could lead to significant public backlash and potential customer loss for the ISPs.\n\nIt's also important to note that actions by ISPs would likely be influenced by regulatory oversight, market competition, and public opinion, making total blocking of major platforms less likely but not impossible in the absence of net neutrality.",
